<!-- POEM START -->
<table width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="margin:30px 0;">
  <tr>
    <td align="center">
      <table width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"
        style="border:1px solid #e6e6e6; border-radius:8px; background:#fafafa; padding:22px;">
        <tr>
          <td style="font-family:Times, serif; color:#333;">

            <div style="font-size:20px; font-style:italic; text-align:center; margin-bottom:18px;">
              To Honor Our Very Essence
            </div>
              <div style="
  max-width: 600px;
  margin: 0 auto;
  padding: 18px 16px;
  font-family: Georgia, 'Times New Roman', serif;
  font-size: 17px;
  line-height: 1.25;
  color: #111111;
">
It’s important to give attention to<br>
The rivers, creeks, streams, runoffs, condensations, fog banks, lagoons and oceans<br>
The rains, mists, showers, storms, hurricanes, tempests and crashing waves<br>
The pipes, puddles and wells<br>
The wastewater treatment and saltwater intrusion<br>
The frost and the vapor<br>
All have roles, good or bad<br>
Ultimately always good<br>
<br>
We are inside out fish<br>
Creatures evolved to hold the primordial ocean within us<br>
Thus, in order to honor<br>
Our very essence<br>
We must honor the water<br>
<br>
Water’s currents carry time<br>
And can carry us through it<br>
If you gave a spring a microphone<br>
Who would it talk about?<br>
Politicians who claim to rule<br>
But never visit<br>
Or those who dip their hands, paws, tails, tongues and toes<br>
In its bubbles of insulated streams?<br>
<br>
<img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/lueeisa/newsforgetterletter/refs/heads/main/water3.gif" width="200" style="height:auto; display:block; margin:0;">
<br>
What story would it tell?<br>
The last 200 years, a blink<br>
Of a glacier’s eye<br>
Or the full geologic story<br>
From undersea sediment to uplifting<br>
To tens of thousands of years of indigenous stewardship?<br>
<br>
Water can shape a city<br>
Tell us where to build and where to not<br>
Until we put a levee over its mouth<br>
And we turn our building windows away<br>
From its beautiful banks<br>
So we can’t see it either<br>
<br>
What is the cost of ignoring<br>
What feeds us?<br>
What gives us delight?<br>
Where we’re from?<br>
<br>
The waters of the world<br>
All have roles, good or bad<br>
(read: inconvenient)<br>
Ultimately always good<br>
<br>
Water’s currents carry time<br>
And can carry us through it<br>
Especially now, as we approach<br>
The cliff’s edge of climatic instability<br>
In order to honor<br>
Our very essence<br>
We must honor the water
            </div>
            <div style="max-width: 600px; font-size:14px; color:#777; text-align:right; margin-top:18px; font-style:italic;">
              — Emily A.
            </div>

          </td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </td>
  </tr>
</table>
